Since the type of variable `a` is [class] `A`, the variable can only access members and methods of class `A` (depending on the access specifiers) &amp;ndash; even though the actual type of variable `a` is class `B`.

Refer to method [paintComponent](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.desktop/javax/swing/JComponent.html#paintComponent(java.awt.Graphics)), in class `javax.swing.JComponent`. The type of the method parameter is `Graphics` but the actual type of the parameter is [Graphics2D](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.desktop/java/awt/Graphics2D.html) (which extends `Graphics`). However, in order to access the methods of `Graphics2D`, you must first cast the parameter, i.e.
```java
Graphics2D g2d = (Graphics2D) g;
```
This is a fundamental aspect of the object-oriented paradigm.  
Refer also to the [comment](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/75082053/java-accesing-properties-with-same-name-in-both-classes#comment132497170_75082053) to your question by @ArunSudhakaran

Similarly, if you want variable `a` to access the `w` member of class `B`, you need to cast `a`.
```java
A a = new B();
if (a instanceof B) {
    B b = (B) a;
    System.out.println(b.w);
}
```
If you are using at least Java 14, you can use [Pattern Matching for the instanceof Operator](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/14/language/pattern-matching-instanceof-operator.html)
```java
A a = new B();
if (a instanceof B b) {
    System.out.println(b.w);
}
```
Also refer to the book [Effective Java](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/effective-java-3rd/9780134686097/) by Josh Bloch.

